issue.title: Support for int64 with webgl backend of the web runtime

repository.name: onnxruntime

issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Here's a working demo of [AnimeGANv2](https://huggingface.co/spaces/akhaliq/AnimeGANv2) with ONNX Runtime Web: https://josephrocca.github.io/anime-gan-v2-web/onnx.html The wasm backend works, but if you switch it to the webgl backend with the drop-down selector on that page, it gives the error "int64 is not supported":

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1167575/141192627-2c0c1f2d-8365-42dd-9b93-f682481c3554.png)

I'm wondering whether it's possible for the webgl backend to support this model? [Here's the onnx model](https://github.com/josephrocca/anime-gan-v2-web/blob/main/anime-gan-v2.onnx) that I'm trying to execute.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): onnxruntime-web@1.9.0

**Describe the solution you'd like**
I'd like to be able to use the webgl backend for this model (purely for performance reasons). I don't know enough about the ONNX web runtime or the webgl backend to give any details on the best way to approach a solution here.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
The wasm backend is fine, but I'm guessing there would be a significant speedup for a model like this if it could use the GPU.

---

Thanks for your work on ONNX Runtime Web! I was pleasantly surprised to see that the wasm backend worked on my first try. Meanwhile converting the original Pytorch model to tfjs and tflite has led to some errors that I've yet to resolve.

issue.title: Does inference in Javascript support XGBoost models?

labels.name: stale
labels.description: issues that have not been addressed in a while; categorized by a bot

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**

When I try to load in an XGBoost model using code adapted from https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-inference-examples/blob/main/js/quick-start_onnxruntime-web-script-tag/index.html, I get the following error: ```ReferenceError: Buffer is not defined.```

**Main question: is this likely because XGBoost models are not supported for inference in JS, or is it because there is some other problem?**

Here is the code I used. I run the code within [Electron](https://github.com/electron/electron-quick-start). The error occurs in the second line (`const session = await ort.InferenceSession.create('./rf_iris.onnx');`) since `Loaded model` is not printed.  If I replace the model with another one, e.g. `model.onnx` in the [JS example](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-inference-examples/tree/main/js/quick-start_onnxruntime-web-script-tag), this code runs fine (with small adjustments to the model input and output names).

```
// "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/onnxruntime-web/dist/ort.min.js" is loaded in index.html before calling this script
async function main() {

 // create a new session and load the specific model.
 console.log('Try to load model')
 const session = await ort.InferenceSession.create('./rf_iris.onnx');
 console.log('Loaded model')
 // prepare inputs. a tensor need its corresponding TypedArray as data
 const dataA = Float32Array.from([1, 20, 466, 0]);
 const tensorA = new ort.Tensor('float32', dataA, [1, 4]);

 // prepare feeds. use model input names as keys.
 const feeds = { float_input: tensorA};

 // feed inputs and run
 const results = await session.run(feeds);

 // read from results
 console.log('Got results')
 const dataC = results.probabilities.data;
 console.log(`data of result tensor 'probabilities': ${dataC}`);
}

main();
```

I have included details about the XGBoost model in the Additional context section. You can also [find it here](https://github.com/jessicayung/artifacts-for-github-issues/blob/main/rf_iris.onnx).

**Urgency**
Ideally by 4 Oct for a project.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux Ubuntu 20.04.2 LTS (Windows Subsystem for Linux 2)
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary (pip install in conda env)
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.9.0
- Python version: 3.6.13
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): (not relevant, but 1.60.2)
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): n/a
- CUDA/cuDNN version: n/a
- GPU model and memory: n/a

**To Reproduce**
- Run the code above within an index.html (e.g. as is done [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-inference-examples/blob/main/js/quick-start_onnxruntime-web-script-tag/index.html)) with [the ONNX model here](https://github.com/jessicayung/artifacts-for-github-issues/blob/main/rf_iris.onnx). 

**Additional context**
The XGBoost model was trained and saved using this code, which was taken from another issue:

```
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import onnxmltools
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from skl2onnx.common.data_types import FloatTensorType

# Train a XGBoost model.
iris = load_iris()
X, y = iris.data, iris.target
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y)
clr = XGBClassifier()
clr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Convert into ONNX format
initial_type = [('float_input', FloatTensorType([None, 4]))]
onx = onnxmltools.convert.convert_xgboost(clr, initial_types=initial_type)
with open("rf_iris.onnx", "wb") as f:
 f.write(onx.SerializeToString())
```
I have checked that it runs fine in Python using this code:
```
# ONNX Runtime
import onnxruntime as rt
import numpy as np
sess = rt.InferenceSession("rf_iris.onnx")
input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
label_name = sess.get_outputs()[1].name

# Sample Test Input

predict_list = [1., 20., 466., 0.]
predict_array = np.array(predict_list).reshape((1,-1))

# Prediction from ONNX Runtime
pred_onx = sess.run([label_name], {input_name: predict_array.astype(np.float32)})[0]
print("Prediction of ONNX Runtime", pred_onx)
```

Thank you!

body: "Buffer" is a Node.js type and should not be used in browser. I will try if I can reproduce this issue. (I cannot reproduce the error described in #9757)

@fs-eire You can't reproduce it [at this url](https://josephrocca.github.io/anime-gan-v2-web/onnx.html)? That's strange - perhaps you didn't switch the drop-down menu to webgl? You can see the usage of `Buffer` by searching for `Buffer.from` (Ctrl+F) in [ort.js v1.9.0](https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/onnxruntime-web@1.9.0/dist/ort.js) (line 11711, for example). Here's a video showing the bug in Firefox v94 and Chrome v95 (latest versions):


https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1167575/141874644-2b8a92f3-3d54-4e51-9c97-9996c15ed0da.mp4
I can reproduce it now. Looks like it uses Buffer for string encoding/decoding in attribute. I will do a fix on that
